            <!-- Review 1: The Remains of the Day -->
            <div class="book-card">
                <div class="book-cover">ðŸ“•</div>
                <div class="book-info">
                    <h2 class="book-title">The Remains of the Day</h2>
                    <p class="book-author">Kazuo Ishiguro</p>
                    <div class="book-rating">â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…</div>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        Ishiguro's masterpiece is a devastating portrait of emotional repression and wasted
                        opportunities. Narrated by Stevens, an English butler whose unwavering devotion to
                        duty has cost him love and authentic human connection, the novel unfolds through
                        increasingly unreliable recollections.
                    </p>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        What makes this extraordinary is how Ishiguro mirrors form and contentâ€”Stevens's
                        meticulously controlled prose is the linguistic equivalent of his emotional constraint.
                        The gaps, hesitations, and euphemisms reveal more than direct statements ever could.
                    </p>
                    <span class="book-annotation">
                        A quietly devastating meditation on regret and the human capacity for self-deception.
                    </span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Review 2: Educated -->
            <div class="book-card">
                <div class="book-cover">ðŸ“˜</div>
                <div class="book-info">
                    <h2 class="book-title">Educated</h2>
                    <p class="book-author">Tara Westover</p>
                    <div class="book-rating">â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜†</div>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        Tara Westover's memoir chronicles her journey from a survivalist family in rural Idaho
                        to earning a PhD from Cambridge. Raised without formal education, Westover's path required
                        not just intellectual growth but painful reconstruction of her entire worldview.
                    </p>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        The book's power lies in Westover's honesty about the complexity of leaving behind family.
                        Education transformed her, but at tremendous cost. She resists easy narratives, acknowledging
                        both the abuse and the genuine love that existed.
                    </p>
                    <span class="book-annotation">
                        Powerful testament to resilience and the price of self-creation.
                    </span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Review 3: Never Let Me Go -->
            <div class="book-card">
                <div class="book-cover">ðŸ“—</div>
                <div class="book-info">
                    <h2 class="book-title">Never Let Me Go</h2>
                    <p class="book-author">Kazuo Ishiguro</p>
                    <div class="book-rating">â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…</div>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        Another Ishiguro masterpiece. This dystopian novel follows students at an English boarding
                        school who gradually discover they're clones raised to donate organs. What could be sensational
                        becomes, in Ishiguro's hands, a profound meditation on mortality and identity.
                    </p>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        The genius lies in restraint. The horror isn't dramatized but accepted with quiet resignation.
                        The characters' passive acceptance mirrors our own relationship with mortalityâ€”we know death is
                        coming, yet we focus on smaller concerns.
                    </p>
                    <span class="book-annotation">
                        Haunting exploration of what gives life meaning when death is certain.
                    </span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Review 4: Sapiens -->
            <div class="book-card">
                <div class="book-cover">ðŸ“™</div>
                <div class="book-info">
                    <h2 class="book-title">Sapiens</h2>
                    <p class="book-author">Yuval Noah Harari</p>
                    <div class="book-rating">â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜†</div>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        Harari's ambitious sweep through human history identifies three major revolutions: Cognitive,
                        Agricultural, and Scientific. His central thesis: humans conquered the world through our unique
                        ability to believe in shared fictionsâ€”nations, religions, corporations, money.
                    </p>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        The book excels at reframing familiar history. Harari argues the Agricultural Revolution was
                        "history's biggest fraud." However, breadth comes at the expense of depth. Some arguments feel
                        oversimplified, and speculation is occasionally presented as fact.
                    </p>
                    <span class="book-annotation">
                        Thought-provoking overview that challenges conventional wisdom about human progress.
                    </span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Review 5: Blood Meridian -->
            <div class="book-card">
                <div class="book-cover">ðŸ“•</div>
                <div class="book-info">
                    <h2 class="book-title">Blood Meridian</h2>
                    <p class="book-author">Cormac McCarthy</p>
                    <div class="book-rating">â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…</div>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        McCarthy's brutal masterpiece follows a teenage runaway who joins a gang of scalp hunters
                        in 1850s Mexico. The violence is unrelenting, biblical in scale, rendered in prose that
                        oscillates between stark minimalism and baroque grandeur.
                    </p>
                    <p class="book-review">
                        At the novel's dark heart is Judge Holdenâ€”one of literature's most terrifying creations.
                        The Judge represents violence as fundamental to human existence, a philosophy the novel
                        neither endorses nor refutes. McCarthy presents evil without explanation or redemption.
                    </p>
                    <span class="book-annotation">
                        Not for everyone. But if you can stomach it: essential American literature.
                    </span>
                </div>
            </div>
